<owl:NamedIndividual rdf:about="#exploratoryobservation15">
  <rdf:type rdf:resource="#ExploratoryObservation"/>
  <finding rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Specific Comments: The noise appears to be uncorrelated. With this dataset, it is reasonable to use the first 5 components to approximate the signal and the remainder to be noise. The first component seems uncorrelated with the others. Since the Durbin-Watson statistic is in the 1.5 to 2.5 range (1.7), we can treat the noise as independent Further, PELT reported no change points in the noise, so we can treat the noise as Independent Identically Distributed If your downstream task, needs to approximate the data as the sum of a smooth signal with IID noise, with this data, it is a reasonable choice. For this dataset, Monte-Carlo simulation may be a reasonable assumption. We can think of other realizations of this dataset to be. similar to this dataset, for the entire period. The signal components lie within the confidence intervals obtained from the simulation.</finding>
  <finding_sequence rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#integer">14</finding_sequence>
  <exploratory_observation_type rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Data Quality Observation</exploratory_observation_type>
  <intent rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">DATA_UNDERSTANDING</intent>
</owl:NamedIndividual>


